# [[ project_name ]]

[[ project_description ]]

A Turborepo monorepo (pnpm workspaces) sharing one UI and one Supabase backend
across web and native:

- `apps/web` — Next.js 16 (App Router, Turbopack), deploys to Vercel.
- `apps/native` — Expo (SDK 54, expo-router v6), ships through EAS.
- `packages/app` — shared screens, with navigation via Solito v5.
- `packages/ui` — Tamagui design system (shared components, tokens, themes).
- `packages/api` — Supabase client factory and the heavy-compute (Modal) seam.
- `packages/types` — generated Supabase types plus shared domain types.
- `packages/config` — base tsconfig and shared config.

## Getting started

```bash
pnpm install
pnpm --filter web dev      # Next.js on http://localhost:3000
pnpm --filter native start # Expo dev server
```

`pnpm dev` runs every app through Turborepo at once; in day-to-day work you
usually target one app with `--filter`.

## Environment

Copy the top-level `.env.example` to `.env` and fill in the Supabase values.
Client-safe keys use the `sb_publishable_*` family and are exposed through
`NEXT_PUBLIC_*` (web) and `EXPO_PUBLIC_*` (native). The `sb_secret_*` key is
server-only and never reaches a client bundle.

## Supabase types

Regenerate `packages/types/database.ts` from your project schema with the
Supabase CLI:

```bash
supabase gen types typescript --linked > packages/types/database.ts
```

## Heavy compute (Modal)

`packages/api/heavy-compute.ts` is the seam for long-running or GPU work. It
calls a Supabase Edge Function wrapper (preferred) or a direct HTTPS Modal
endpoint. It stays off the hot CRUD and auth path and never holds a secret key.

## Native build

The native binary needs the EAS cloud toolchain (`eas build`, configured in
`apps/native/eas.json`) or a local Xcode / Android SDK. A plain container can
build and run the web app but cannot produce a native binary.

## Lighter alternative: Next.js export + Capacitor

If the mobile surface is essentially the web UI in a shell, you can drop Expo
and EAS entirely: build the web app as a static export (`next build` with
`output: 'export'`) and wrap it with Capacitor for iOS and Android. That gives
one render path and a simpler toolchain at the cost of WebView performance and
true native UI. Choose Capacitor when you want a single web codebase in a native
shell; choose this Expo + Tamagui + Solito setup when you need real native
navigation, native modules, and platform-authentic UI with shared components.
